article.description: DeMya Walker had 11 points and a career-high 10 rebounds as Portland sent Detroit to a league-record ninth straight loss to open the season, 67-60 Saturday night.
article.headline: Worst start in WNBA history reaches 0-9
article.linkText: Fire extend road-weary Shock's awful start to 0-9
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The WNBA's youngest team got another
painful road lesson Saturday night.

The Detroit Shock -- whose average age is 23.7, a full year younger than any other team -- twice came within three points of tying the game, but never got closer.

DeMya Walker had 11 points and a career-high 10 rebounds as Portland sent Detroit to a league-record ninth straight loss to open the season, 67-60 Saturday night.

``We played hard the whole game,'' Portland coach Linda Hargrove
said. ``We played great defense when we needed to.''

The Shock have played seven of their first nine games on the
road and play their next game in Washington on Tuesday before
returning home.

Detroit went on a 7-0 run to get within 58-55 with 1:25
remaining. But Kristin Folkl converted a 3-point play with 56
seconds left and the Shock would not score again until the game was
already decided.

Alisa Burras scored 14 points and had six rebounds for the Fire (3-5), who won for the third time in four games after dropping their first four. Ukari Figgs added 13 points.

Wendy Palmer led the Shock (0-9) with 14 points. Astou
Ndiaye-Diatta added 13 points and Swin Cash had 12 rebounds.

``We've tried to stay positive with them and our team has continued to play very hard even though we're 0-9,'' Detroit coach Greg Williams said. ``We haven't laid down.''

The Fire jumped ahead early 16-8 with a 10-0 run. Detroit spent
the rest of the half catching up, pulling to within five at 27-22.

But Figgs hit a 19-foot jumper to beat the shot clock and later
added a 3-pointer to put the Fire up by 10 at the half, 38-28.

   Portland shot 51.6 percent in the first half but followed that
up by shooting 24.2 percent in the second.

Jackie Stiles entered the game with 11:31 left in the first half
for her first action since June 2 against Seattle. Stiles,
sidelined the previous four games with bursitis in her right heel,
scored six points on 2-for-7 shooting in 11 minutes.

``I felt a lot better,'' Stiles said. ``My timing was a little
off, but this was the first time that I had done anything
full-court. I felt pretty good overall.''

Portland's Sylvia Crawley went scoreless in 21 minutes and was
0-for-10 from the field,'' the first time in her WNBA career she
did not score.

``There was a time that if Sylvia went 0-for-10 in a game we
wouldn't have a chance to win,'' Hargrove said. ``We fell really
good about our post rotation and depth.''
